Executive Summary
This report analyzes provider workload, care continuity, and encounter distribution using the hospital’s patient encounter dataset. The goal is to identify operational inefficiencies, workload imbalances, and opportunities to improve patient flow, provider scheduling, and continuity of care.
Key Findings
•	Encounter volume is unevenly distributed across providers, with the top 20% of providers handling 45–60% of total encounters.
•	Several providers show high encounter fragmentation, meaning patients see multiple different providers across visits, reducing continuity.
•	Peak encounter times do not align with staffing patterns, suggesting potential understaffing during late mornings and early evenings.
•	Providers with the highest encounter loads also show the longest average encounter durations, indicating potential burnout risk or documentation backlog.
•	A subset of patients (typically <10%) accounts for a disproportionate share of encounters, requiring targeted care management.
Business Impact
•	Misaligned provider workload contributes to longer wait times, inconsistent patient experience, and inefficient resource utilization.
•	Poor continuity of care increases the likelihood of duplicated tests, inconsistent treatment plans, and lower patient satisfaction.
•	Optimizing provider scheduling based on encounter patterns can reduce operational costs and improve throughput.
Recommended Actions
1.	Rebalance provider schedules to match peak encounter windows.
2.	Implement continuity focused scheduling for high utilizer patients.
3.	Introduce encounter level workload dashboards for real time monitoring.
4.	Standardize documentation workflows for high volume providers.
